The only negative thing I could think of the movie was how scrawny the #BlackPanther 's legs were and it's only because my friend whom I was with kept mentioning that. I guess the movie could have been longer too.

The second greatest thing about #BlackPanther was the women. Everyone of them stole the spotlight when they were on screen. #Shuri is my fav character in the movie and I need her to take the Panther helm in the sequel even if it's for a short time.

Killmonger is, without a doubt, the best marvel movie villain ever. I can't remember last time I watched a movie and felt conflicted about which side I was on at the end of it. Kudos to Michael B Jordan for such a powerhouse performance.
Removing all the fantasy and technology, Black Panther would still have been a compelling movie. Please let Ryan Coogler direct any movie that he wants. His talent as a director has no bound.

The greatest thing about the movie for me was that it was grounded in reality. I can't think of any other superhero movie I've seen where part of myself wasn't telling me that shit is just a fantasy. That side of brain went numb watching #BlackPanther
Just came back from seeing #BlackPanther. I thought I was ready and had my expectation already too high but I was still blown away.

I already know 2018 will be a great year for me. I hope it will be the same for everyone else. I wish y'all much success, peace, love, and happiness.
I created enough quality work that I am proud of, racked up on publications, and expanded my footprints to new markets. More importantly I built a solid foundation for what's ahead.

Besides having to deal with identity theft and my bank account being wiped clean, 2017 was a decent year personally. It's the first year since I moved to NYC where I feel like I actually did enough to get where I need to be.

@MyBlackMatters 11. Last one: be a decent human being. College is part of the real world. If u come out of it f up, chance is u won't b any different after.
@MyBlackMatters 10b. There should also be other way to get free/cheap food on campus like networking events, vegan society, Hare Krishna, etc
@MyBlackMatters 10a. If you can't afford food, join student orgs that offers free food at their meetings. Don't just live on Ramen if that's still a thing.
@MyBlackMatters 9b. I know each school has different system. But you can probably withdraw from a class or take the whole semester off to figure things out
@MyBlackMatters 9a. If things get too tough for you, make sure to discuss options with ur advisor instead of suffering or giving up completely.
@MyBlackMatters 8. College can be stressful af. Make sure to use the resources available to you for your wellbeing (clinic, free therapy session, gym, etc)
@MyBlackMatters 5. Don't be afraid to be yourself 6. Find other students that share the same interest as you 7. Don't be afraid to ask for help when needed
@MyBlackMatters 4. Invest time in picking up skills outside of your major. I was doing Mech Eng; picked up photography and Software Eng along the way.
@MyBlackMatters 1. Avoid taking out loans 2. Don't waste your summers. Get a job, internship, research, volunteer, etc  3. Get to know the faculty members

In 2 years,  I definitely don't wanna be in this same situation.  I work too damn hard to not make it.
But I do need to work smarter tho. I must be a better businessman.  There are ppl out there w/ less talent than me living on their dream.
For now I'm OK being the guy that keep chipping away at making his dream come true while working on some other dude's dreams.
No disrespect to any starving artist out there.  I'm actually jealous of some of you guys who get to do what you love 24/7
I also don't see myself being a starving artist,  not knowing where rent money is coming from,  and having to use ppl to make it.pic.twitter.com/dsSjSpNpTL
I don't see myself being at an office 12 hrs a day, hating my coworkers,  not having time to create,  just for more money.pic.twitter.com/rtiVDgCLoM
Twice since I've been here,  I convinced myself to take a break from photography to look for a higher paying job. Ended up wasting 4 months
But it also prevented me from moving up in the corporate ladder and making more money.  Easily 3x what I'm making now.
Keeping the same job from FL when I moved gave me more time to actually work on my art and took me away from the office which I despise.
The best thing about this situation is I have been working at home for the past 2.5 years.  Perk of being a valuable asset to a company
I haven't had a chance to actually settle down for the past 2.5 years.  And I know being able to do so mentally is where I excel the most.
I looked back and realized within that plan,  I didn't account for a breakup,  a year of depression,  moving to NYC,  moving 7 times in NYC
I woke up both yesterday and today with my mind telling me: "Bruh!  What happened to ur plan??"  And my bank account: "Negro,  u are broke"pic.twitter.com/scYRjwBMzE
Took a year for me to get a job and had to throw away my mechanical engineering degree to work software. I still kept the 5 year plan tho.
After college,  I had a five year "plan" to leave the cubicle nation.  Plan is in quotation cause it wasn't.  I never wrote anything down.
Today is my five year anniversary in the corporate world.  Most ppl who knows me don't know that I'm also Software Engineer.
